<BaseLayout title="Rimmer Fish" description="Great River fish that come from the sea both ways.">
  <section class="page-section">
    <p class="eyebrow">World · Animals</p>
    <h1>Rimmer Fish</h1>
    <p class="lede">Blue-green Great River fish that come from the sea both ways and move through the river in route-sensitive groups.</p>

    <article class="visual-callout visual-callout-world">
      <div class="visual-callout-mark" aria-hidden="true"><span>≈</span></div>
      <div class="visual-callout-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Great River</p>
        <h2>Sea both ways</h2>
        <p>Rimmer Fish belong by the Great River. They are not ordinary river fish and not ordinary sea fish. They carry the strangeness of a river that receives the sea both ways.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Locked rule</h2>
      <p>Rimmer Fish come from the sea both ways.</p>
      <p>This should not be flattened into ordinary upstream and downstream migration. Their movement belongs to the Great River’s own water logic.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>How to recognise it</h2>
      <p>A Rimmer Fish has a deep blue-green body, silver side flashes, pale gold marks near the gills, smooth group movement, and route-like turning patterns.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Sound and movement</h2>
      <p>Rimmer Fish make a low river-pulse. The pulse can sometimes be felt through wet stones, wooden boats, bridge posts, or riverbank roots.</p>
      <p>They move in groups. Their movement suggests more than one direction at once, as if the Great River remembers both directions of the sea.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>What it does in the world</h2>
      <p>Rimmer Fish carry sea minerals, river memory, small drifting life, and route signs between salt-influenced water and river water.</p>
      <p>They help mark the Great River as a living route system.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Related animals</h2>
      <div class="link-list">
        <a href="/world/animals/navan-hart/">Navan Hart</a>
        <a href="/world/animals/mosskeep-frog/">Mosskeep Frog</a>
        <a href="/world/animals/">Animals of Vaelinya</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Accessibility note</p>
      <p>Rimmer Fish are blue-green fish of the Great River. They come from the sea both ways and move through the river in groups that show route and tide memory.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
